<activity xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="act-5-3-1">
<statement>
<p>Evaluate each of the following indefinite integrals. Check each antiderivative that you find by differentiating.

      <ol label="a." cols="2">
        <li><p><m>\int \sin(8-3x) \, dx</m></p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \sec^2 (4x) \, dx</m></p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \frac{1}{11x - 9} \, dx</m></p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \csc(2x+1) \cot(2x+1) \, dx</m></p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-16x^2}}\, dx</m></p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int 5^{-x}\, dx</m></p></li>
      </ol>
      </p>
</statement>
      <hint>
        <p>

        <ol label="a.">
          <li><p>Think <m>\int \sin(u) \, du</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Think <m>\int \sec^2 (u) \, du</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Think <m>\int \frac{1}{u}\, du</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Think <m>\int \csc(u) \cot(u) \, du</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Think <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-u^2}} \, du</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p>Think <m>\int 5^{u} \, du</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
        </p>
      </hint>

      <answer>
        <p>

        <ol label="a.">
        <li><p><m>\int \sin(8-3x) \, dx = -\frac{1}{3} (-\cos(8-3x)) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \sec^2 (4x) \, dx = \frac{1}{4} \tan(4x) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \frac{1}{11x - 9} \, dx = \frac{1}{11} \ln(11x - 9) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \csc(2x+1) \cot(2x+1) \, dx = -\frac{1}{2}\cot(2x+1) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-16x^2}}\, dx = \frac{1}{4} \arcsin(4x) + C</m></p></li>

        <li><p><m>\int 5^{-x}\, dx = -\frac{1}{\ln(5)}5^{-x} + C</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>

      <solution>
        <p>

        <ol label="a.">
        <li><p>Since <m>u=8-3x</m> is linear and <m>\int \sin(u) \, \du = -\cos(u) + C</m>, it follows that <m>\int \sin(8-3x) \, dx = -\frac{1}{3} (-\cos(8-3x)) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p>Since <m>4x</m> is linear and <m>\int \sec^2(u) \, du = \tan(u) + C </m>, we see <m>\int \sec^2 (4x) \, dx = \frac{1}{4} \tan(4x) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p>Using the fact that <m>\int \frac{1}{u} \, du = \ln |u| + C</m>, we have <m>\int \frac{1}{11x - 9} \, dx = \frac{1}{11} \ln(11x - 9) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p>We know <m>\int \csc(u) \cot(u) \, du = -\cot(u) + C</m>, so <m>\int \csc(2x+1) \cot(2x+1) \, dx = -\frac{1}{2}\cot(2x+1) + C</m>.</p></li>

        <li><p>Observe that <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-u^2}}\, dx = \arcsin(u) + C</m>, and thus viewing <m>16x^2 = (4x)^2</m>, we see that <m>\int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-16x^2}}\, dx = \frac{1}{4} \arcsin(4x) + C</m></p></li>

        <li><p>Since <m>\int 5^{u}\, du = \frac{1}{\ln(5)}5^u + C</m>, we have that <m>\int 5^{-x}\, dx = -\frac{1}{\ln(5)}5^{-x} + C</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>


